## Chemical and Physical Safety Standards

The table below covers the most common chemical and safety-related checks relevant to EU scarf exports.

| Test Item | Test Method | Minimum EU Market Requirement | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Fiber Composition** | ISO 1833 (chemical dissolution) | Difference between label claim and test result ≤ 3% | Single-fiber products: 0% tolerance; blends: ±3% |
| **pH Value** | ISO 3071 | 4.0–7.5 for products in direct skin contact | Baby products (Class I): 4.0–7.0 |
| **Formaldehyde Content** | ISO 14184-1 | ≤ 75 mg/kg for direct skin contact | Baby products: ≤ 20 mg/kg |
| **Azo Dyes / Released Aromatic Amines** | ISO 14362-1 | Not detectable (detection limit: 20 mg/kg) | REACH Annex XVII Entry 43 |
| **Nickel Release** | EN 1811 | < 0.5 μg/cm²/week | Relevant only for metallic components |
| **Hexavalent Chromium (Cr VI)** | ISO 17075 | ≤ 3 mg/kg | Mainly relevant to leather parts and trims |
| **PFAS** | CEN/TS 15968 | Total < 100 μg/m² | Requirements tightened significantly after 2025 |
| **Phthalates** | ISO 14389 | DEHP + DBP + BBP ≤ 0.1% | Relevant for plastics, prints, coatings |

### Technical note

In actual scarf production, the highest chemical risk does not always come from the yarn. It often comes from:
- after-treatment chemicals
- coatings
- decorative attachments
- packaging contamination

That is why a supplier declaration alone is not enough when product risk is high.

