## Color Fastness Standards

Color fastness is one of the most commercially sensitive parts of scarf QC because it directly affects wear experience and returns.

| Test Item | Test Method | Minimum EU Market Requirement | Common Commercial Target |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Dry Rubbing Fastness** | ISO 105-X12 | ≥ Grade 4 | Dark shades may be accepted at Grade 3–4 |
| **Wet Rubbing Fastness** | ISO 105-X12 | ≥ Grade 3 | Dark navy / black should still achieve ≥ Grade 3 |
| **Water Fastness** | ISO 105-E01 | ≥ Grade 3–4 (staining) | Color change should be ≥ Grade 4 |
| **Perspiration Fastness** | ISO 105-E04 | ≥ Grade 3–4 (staining) | Both acidic and alkaline perspiration tested |
| **Wash Fastness** | ISO 105-C06 | ≥ Grade 4 (color change) | Based on 40°C wash program |
| **Light Fastness** | ISO 105-B02 | ≥ Grade 4 | Light shades may be accepted at ≥ Grade 3 |
| **Saliva Fastness** | EN 71-3 | Migration limits apply | Relevant for baby/children’s products |

### Commercial interpretation

A scarf may technically pass minimum requirements and still be rejected by a buyer if the color performance does not match the product’s price level.

**Typical market expectation by tier:**
- **Promotional / mass market:** minimum pass level
- **Mid-market retail:** stable commercial performance, fewer edge cases
- **Premium / fashion brand:** higher tolerance control, especially on dark shades and skin-contact products

