## Physical Performance Standards

Physical performance is where a scarf stops being just a “textile” and starts behaving like a commercial product.

| Test Item | Test Method | Minimum EU Market Requirement | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Pilling** | ISO 12945-2 (Martindale) | ≥ Grade 3 at 2000 cycles | General market |
|  |  | ≥ Grade 4 at 2000 cycles | Mid-to-high-end market |
| **Dimensional Stability / Shrinkage** | ISO 6330 + ISO 3759 | ≤ ±3% in length | Based on care instructions |
|  |  | ≤ ±5% in width | Knits may allow slightly wider tolerance |
| **Tensile Strength** | ISO 13934-1 | ≥ 150 N | Typical for woven scarves |
| **Bursting Strength** | ISO 13938-2 | ≥ 100 kPa | Typical for knitted scarves |
| **Seam Slippage** | ISO 13936-2 | ≤ 6 mm | For sewn areas |
| **Skew / Distortion** | AATCC 179 | ≤ 3% | Common concern for woven prints |
| **Edge Curling** | Visual + measurement | Edge lift after flat lay ≤ 1.5 cm | Common in knitted styles |

### Why this matters commercially

A scarf is a relatively simple product, which is exactly why buyers expect fewer excuses.  
If pilling is bad, if shrinkage is unstable, or if edge curl ruins presentation, the product immediately feels cheap — no matter how good the yarn claim sounds on paper.

