## OEKO-TEX Standard 100 Product Class Reference

OEKO-TEX is not an EU law, but it remains one of the most commercially useful third-party trust standards for scarf buyers.

| Product Class | Typical Scarf Type | Key Limit Differences vs Class II |
|---|---|---|
| **Class I (Baby)** | Infant scarves and 0–3 years accessories | Formaldehyde ≤ 16 mg/kg; pH 4.0–7.0 |
| **Class II (Direct Skin Contact)** | Adult scarves, shawls, wraps | Formaldehyde ≤ 75 mg/kg; pH 4.0–7.5 |
| **Class III (Non-direct Skin Contact)** | Heavy winter scarves worn over outerwear | Formaldehyde ≤ 150 mg/kg |
| **Class IV (Decoration)** | Decorative textile accessories | Formaldehyde ≤ 300 mg/kg |

### Commercial use

For most adult scarves, **Class II** is the most relevant benchmark.  
If you are selling to fashion brands, department stores, or premium retailers, buyers often expect OEKO-TEX alignment even when they do not explicitly ask for the certificate upfront.

